AB To date the effectiveness of inducing lower-calorie choices by providing
   consumers with calorie information has yielded mixed results. Here four
   controlled experiments show that adding dish-specific calorie
   information to menus (calorie posting) tends to result in lower-calorie
   choices. However, additionally grouping low-calorie dishes into a single
   low-calorie category (calorie organizing) ironically diminishes the
   positive effects of calorie posting. This outcome appears to be caused
   by the effect that grouping low-calorie options has on consumers
   consideration sets. When choosing from a calorie-organized menu,
   consumers are more likely to filter out low-calorie options in the early
   noncompensatory screening stages of the decision process and,
   consequently, are less likely to choose low-calorie options. This result
   disappears when consumers deliberate longer before choosing. These
   results are important for consumer welfare as well-intentioned
   restaurateurs (policy makers) may be tempted to institute (mandate) the
   calorie organization of menus, inadvertently resulting in consumers
   choosing higher-calorie meals.
