AB Consumer choice is often based on the relative visual appeal of
   competing products. Lay intuition, common marketing practice, and extant
   literature all suggest that more visual impressions help consumers
   distinguish products. This research shows that the opposite can occur.
   Rather than highlighting differences, seeing more pictures of products
   being compared can obfuscate perceptions, reduce distinctiveness and
   attractiveness of products, and increase choice uncertainty. Six
   experiments demonstrate that this "product-agnosia" effect is driven by
   shifts in the perceptual focus level of visual information processing.
   More visual impressions increased component-oriented and decreased
   gestalt-oriented perceptual focus, which undermined the distinctiveness
   of products distinguished on a gestalt level (e.g., by style). The
   effect reversed for products distinguished on a component level (e.g.,
   by technical features). Overall, the efficacy of "showing more" depended
   on matching consumers' visual-processing style and the level (gestalt
   vs. component) at which products are differentiated.
