AB Hanging up our coat, tidying our desk, classifying our books, what
   meanings do these mundane practices convey? Extending Mary Douglas's
   work, this article investigates tidiness from the angle of symbolic
   pollution. Based on photo-elicitation, it shows that, similarly to
   symbolic pollution described at a macro-social level, tidiness depends
   on two conditions, namely, a set of classifications and the dangerous
   transgression of these classifications. However, at a micro-social
   level, individuals negotiate boundaries between classifications in order
   to cope with symbolic pollution. Consumers define their domestic
