   by imbuing it with a zeitgeist value and the heir's presence, helping
   the heir to better navigate her imaginaries of the past, present, and
   future. Beyond the ritualistic consumption or curation of heirlooms, our
   findings reveal a creative, playful, and proactive relation with
   heirlooms, evocative of craftwork. Moreover, the market, within
   particular boundaries, can help authenticate heirloom objects and
   facilitate their inalienability rather than necessarily destroying their
   authenticity. Our study has implications for the role of heirloom
   consumption in consumers' negotiations of continuity and change, the
   interaction of the symbolic and the material in heirlooms, and the
