AB Even though 80% of a shopper's time in the store is spent moving from
   place to place, little is known about managing the pace of in-store
   traffic flow. Based on the store atmospherics literature, this article
   introduces interventions to optimize the pace of locomotion. A series of
   lab and field experiments demonstrates that changes in flooring affect
   customers' walking speed. The number, the nature, and the relative
   salience of progress markers along a walking path toward a physical
   location communicate goal progress and thus the motivation to reach a
   particular destination. Consistent with a goal gradient account,
