   product pairs, different consumers hold divergent beliefs about whether
   each pair is a matter of quality (such that one product is objectively
   better) or taste (such that one product is a better match with their own
   personal preferences). These beliefs have meaningful consequences. When
   consumers believe their chosen products are objectively better rather
   than better matches with their preferences: (1) they are willing to pay
